questions.prompt: First appearing in 1905, reaching their heyday at the turn of the decade, and largely supplanted by the teens, the first theaters in the United States to exhibit films exclusively were known by what name (derived in part by the standard price of admission)?

Name the clever and meddlesome young woman, the title character of a novel from 1815, who, after a series of embarrassing errors, realizes eventually that she is in love with the squire George Knightley?

The 1954 song "It Should've Been Me", written by Memphis Curtis and produced by Ahmet Ertegun, was Ray Charles's first hit for what record label, which would release eleven of his albums and dozens of singles before his move to ABC in 1959?
Banking, stock market, and/or economic crises of 1857, 1873, 1893, and 1907 all have common names which include their years and what anxious economic term?
What Frank was crowned "Emperor of the Romans" on Christmas Day in the year 800 CE?

In the history of the New York Yankees, there have been eleven different players to hit 40 home runs in a season, but only three batting solely right-handed:  Alex Rodriguez (2005 and 2007), Aaron Judge (2017), and what third player, a Hall of Famer and drip coffee lover who accomplished the feat one time, in 1937?
